.SS "üß™ C-Unix-STD-Basic-Fork"
.PP
\fBPath:\fP \fCsrc/C-Unix-STD-Basic-Fork/main\&.c\fP
.PP
.PP
.PP
.SS "üéØ Purpose"
.PP
This example demonstrates the \fBbasic behavior of the \fCfork()\fP system call\fP and how a process is \fBduplicated\fP into a parent and a child process\&. 
.PP
The goal is to understand: 
.PP
.PD 0
.IP "\(bu" 2
how to distinguish parent and child processes 
.IP "\(bu" 2
how execution flow is duplicated 
.IP "\(bu" 2
how concurrent processes produce output 
.PP
.PP
.PP
.PP
.SS "üõ†Ô∏è Description"
.PP
The program executes a decreasing \fCfor\fP loop (\fCi = 2 ‚Üí 1\fP)\&. At each iteration: 
.PP
.PD 0
.IP "1." 4
the \fCfork()\fP system call is invoked 
.IP "2." 4
the \fBparent process\fP receives a value greater than \fC0\fP 
.IP "3." 4
the \fBchild process\fP receives \fC0\fP 
.IP "4." 4
based on the return value: 
.PD 0

.IP "  \(bu" 4
the parent prints \fCi\fP 
.IP "  \(bu" 4
the child prints \fC-i\fP 
.PP

.PP
.PP
Since \fCfork()\fP duplicates the current process: 
.PP
.PD 0
.IP "\(bu" 2
after the first iteration there are \fB2 running processes\fP 
.IP "\(bu" 2
after the second iteration there are \fB4 running processes\fP 
.PP
.PP
The order of the printed output is \fBnon-deterministic\fP, because it depends on the operating system scheduler\&. 
.PP
